A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to fight election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by confirming that the US's electoral fraud is less rare than the number of people killed by the lightning.
The Republicans' lawyers have, by the way, recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the US in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for the implementation of the elections in each country.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that make the procedure for registration or order-making difficult.
This phenomenon has become more important after the November 2010 elections, where 675 new Republican representatives were recorded in 26 countries.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, which restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 countries.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time-limits for early voting, declare the right to register as a voter on the election day, and the right of citizens to vote for which there is a judicial act.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state asked the voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act in 2008.
The Republican authorities were in a hurry to extend this practice to other countries.
Over the last two years, they have been promoting draft laws in 34 states, forcing voters to present a photo card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible persons, do not have a photo card issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such a card in 2012.
However, there are often more than a hundred dollars to be paid to get the necessary ID.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affected by young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of people between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the necessary photo ID.
This is still enough.
The students who are considered to be voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo card issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who choose the Republican side more to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state requested a proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws calling on voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish votes.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Spanish voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on the election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide help to those who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the electoral registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections have helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of new voters' registration by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators in five other states have adopted laws aimed at shortening the period of early voting.
For example, in the general elections in Florida in 2008, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were Afro-Americans, although they account for only 13% of the state's voters.
The same applies to the Spanish population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the white people who represented 76% of the voters were only 46% of those who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have adopted laws that require the presentation of a photo card.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the party political nature of the laws adopted and see in them as a clear objective the influence of the results in the countries that are decisive for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that have adopted these laws are 171 out of 270 votes required in the electoral board to win the presidency.
It is too early to be sure that these changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
