The Higgs-Boson analyses
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs Boson has aroused some excitement last summer, and for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not completely certain that this is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely sure about it.
However, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, as it seems that there is only a small risk of being mistaken, and let us look at what is at stake.
There is an inevitable law in this world that does not allow two objects to be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard because you will hurt yourself.
Because even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it is also governed by such a law: the Pauli rule of exclusion, which means that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state," with this "state" as a whole consisting of some of their properties.
On the basis of this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner there are the good citizens, who are called Fermione, who are kind to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a bad gang of anarchists, who are not holy - certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley Laboratories (which is by the way absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs-Boson would somehow be related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this place, in such a way as a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "interference" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carrier of power."
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this Boson is shown.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little similar to a frozen pond whose surface could only be destroyed by a very large rock.
That is why a huge particle accelerator such as CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is in fact not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep on the fridge on its own.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
What can all these research be "good," Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine closely all differences between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, many physicists who hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
One must say that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (up!) and dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (up!).
However, such deviations have not been found in CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to believe that there is no.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was seen in the beginning as a "laboratory toy."
Imagine...
In addition, applications may also result from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves all digital cameras worldwide as the "eye" and has brought him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can really never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With its Committee on Death in Dity, Quebec has recently discussed the sensitive issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look more closely at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that ate him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I made it seven years," he said half-hearted, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease is doing its job: an unmeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating itself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to have his dinner help.
He can even smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicine, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the home Victor-Gadbois.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"This depends on the ability of the person to take a step back," he notes.
For in the opinion of several people working in the palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these steps.
The patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who take care of them will no longer be overtaken with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation."
But because of the disease, I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I no longer have any wishes in life," she says, before she accepts that she has a mask to help her breathe.
She still expects a last visit to her son from Italy in the next few days.
In the home Victor-Gadbois you can offer with a group of volunteers personal care and help with the food intake.
The palliative care is used when there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care on 11.700 inhabitants.
That is very little, considering that one day we will all die.
This is where life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with Brandy or Pepsi, as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died in the course of the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family and patients alike," says Nathalie Savard.
There's no day like the other at the Victor-Gadbois home.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows while he is in his honor, a young man of 36 years old, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, dies in a tragic way after he has tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," Dr. Christiane Martel is concerned.
53% of the patients enrolled in the home Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of the Canadians do not have access to palliative care, that is to say, to a care to relieve the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, at the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the company for domestic palliative care in the Montreal area, are more or less exclusively specialized in the care of cancer patients.
This is precisely the major inadequacy in the health care sector in Quebec, which makes it possible for several doctors specialized in palliative care to avoid the adoption of a law on the regulation of death aid and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent people of the Palliative Care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in order to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not sufficiently powerful to ensure that all have the right to high-quality palliative care before you accept to go to death care.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without taking any measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of the worst forecasts.
The survival chances of Hélène Richard were already minimal when she broke off a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she was sorry to give up the fight, she told me.
But she told me I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the care staff that this wish has not been met after their pain has been reduced by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be made clear that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of the palliative care of the society of domestic palliative care of the Grand Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the end of life, the doctors often use the terminal sedation, which leads to the patient falling asleep either sporadic or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to use this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not reduced say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that does not necessarily mean "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be reduced."
