With 15,000 computers in the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
Some thousand websites accept bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After the rate of Bitcoin reached a maximum of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, it fell to 2 dollars five months later before recovering today to around ten dollars (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive in comparison to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success," "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to the traditional currencies."
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as the "credits" that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes also exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed every time by a central authority.
With bitcoin all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the accounting book, examiners, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
The difference is that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
With the content of the file it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public account accounting book spread throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, who has the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a scrubbing of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "chopped."
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without a link, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task will receive 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to a hundred million, which leaves a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with every improvement in the performance of the calculation.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoin deposits stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol," Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for real money payment and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind
They are accepted by others such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of the bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega-sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converts bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses bitcoin to validate the transactions that are thus cheaper.
The holder also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by the dealers and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are considered in favour of more horizontal-oriented systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, by the way, plans in its report to reassess the various risks considered to be high today in the event of a success of this currency.
