These secrets contain the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous sea road, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, was connected.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to traditions, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda, with which he had a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to walk through the narrow streets named after signs.
Fortuna should be the legend after all who touch the walls in the alley with their sign.
In Jaffa you can find newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo mines.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the crusaders.
In the Roman era, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilatus.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and opera are performed today.
List for tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your poor English knowledge: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is not to be taken in euros but in dollars that can easily be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get on the bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a fast road and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower town to the upper city.
In fact, it's an underground cable car.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which includes a change for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
