"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While MEPs and citizens are discussing the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families that remain in their home country.
On 1 December, a law came into force, according to which every migrant worker must take a test that certifies the knowledge of the Russian language.
To date, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the local housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests are to become a duty for all the host workers in the future.
It is not only a question of language testing, but also of testing in Russian history and the basis of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the maintenance and the extension of the work permit.
Exemptions shall apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
This law also excludes persons who have received their certificates and diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991.
The sense, problem and protection of rights
The whole of the audit bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian Universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 appropriate centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the entry into force of the law in the press, citizens asked the following question several times: what does it actually do?
What changes does the rule of having to provide language skills for both the Russians and the host workers?
In particular, in response to speakers from the Migration Authority, it is about reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says the Head of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebedev.
However, their rights must already be protected from their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
There are problems with migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical examination.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without a language knowledge will inevitably meet people with bad intentions who will put him in a dark, narrow barrack under the pretext of help, where he will stay with dozens of his same months without food and documents and will create 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have many complaints from our migrants.
"The one is promised to you in your home country, and on arrival you will be cheated, get their passports taken off and do not receive the promised wage," the head of the main labour migration administration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov confirms.
Don't be shy, boss!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian Republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they cannot only control the language of the country of destination, but can hardly express themselves in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Usbeken and Tadschiken can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school things.
As teenagers, these children immediately take the first opportunity to make money.
"It is difficult without language knowledge," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Citizens' rights stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the host workers continue to be illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "No access for unauthorised persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
The legalization also costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are largely falsified and we are not registered, and that will result in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tadschike Umed Hushkadamov says to journalists.
"Just don't waste any costs for false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some fake certificates that certify the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by the Federal Migration Authority staff.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get it for free: every migrant who hoped to save himself from the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant three thousand rubles.
The most important direct task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, both officials and citizens' rights are agreed.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise that they will have time for a basic language course to host workers who fall through the test the first time.
In addition, new entrants without language skills are offered places in areas where no active understanding with people is necessary.
Ministry of the Interior ignores illegal arms market
The share of legal weapons in crime is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten up the arms law for private arms owners.
The authorities are thus responding to the recent events: injured in the shooting of weddings and seven dead in the ammo of the Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradow.
The police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in the public and to raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported and promised by the President of the Duma Committee on Security and Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, that the amendments to the arms law will soon be submitted to the Duma.
Not all are satisfied that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "raising the screws."
An open letter was published on the Internet, the author of which - representatives of various arms associations - calls on the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening."
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, the criminal criminal, Vasilij Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
