The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private arms owners will not prevent criminals from serving on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, every possible weapon can be found in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons get to the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts arms orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasian themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel there are illegal weapons that are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the police arms chambers and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other weapons sold illegally come from military weapons camps.
Many military camps have often had explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are numerous private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and, therefore, have the weapons under the control of the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own, sometimes craft production, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in the supply of the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Government Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Critical Literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to the investigators, most of the illegal weapons are from the army and the legal authorities.
Half of the arms in the black market were there because of the "guilt of those responsible for their work in arms," the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons are from conflict areas, 14% are from theft in the production of weapons, and 5% are from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant of a arms store, who does not want to be named, assures that no one has been buying weapons found in the event of illegal excavations for a long time since they are obsolete.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supply in a weapons camp.
A gun, for example a type TT gun, is bought by an Ensign.
The gun is issued and passed through the fence.
"The dealer takes the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says
"The police, of course, know everything and, therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, carry out periodic checks on traders offering illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
