In the US, fast food and supermarket employees strike
Every fourth American youth is at some point behind the Mc Donald's cash register
Over the past few days, there have been massive protests across the US against low wages in Walmart's shops and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will continue to swell or whether they will soon be out of the air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organisations.
In addition to the increase in the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast-food workers, the organizers of the protests aim to set up trade unions.
So far, this sector of the economy has hardly been organised in trade unions.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, on the so-called Black Friday, on which sales were made in the US that attracted millions of customers, which sometimes led to hand-held quantities.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of which 2.2 million are worldwide, laid down their work and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, spread the chain's branches, whose target group are people of low and medium income.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting guns and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in the Walmart branches are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
Therefore, many of the low-paid Walmart employees only buy at their own job.
The prices and the product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart is often able to sell the goods in such a low price because the employees are badly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand scanners.
The participants in the protests on the "Black Friday" called for wage increases and expressed their concern that the contribution to the company's health insurance had increased from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee who makes $9.5 an hour couldn't afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the California University in Berkeley show that if the company increases the average wage to 12 dollars an hour, it would cost Walmart 3.2 billion dollars.
This is about 1.1% more than they are now donating for pay.
If Walmart were to completely kill the wage increases to the customers, every purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
This would be an increase of only 12.39 dollars per year for them compared to today.
Walmart's supporters are pleased to note that only nine states were protesting and that they did not give the company any losses.
The Black Friday lasted the next day in its shop from 8: 00 a.m. on Thursday to midnight, and during that period Walmart sold about 5000 articles per second.
In total, the Walmart-Kassen carried out almost 100 million transactions on "Black Friday."
The company's spokesperson, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the left-wing Huffington Post website that the work was "less than five" Walmart employees and the protest action was just "another PR trick" of the union, which organised the protests.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their goal was not Walmart branches (which are not wanted in this advanced city and are therefore still inexistent), but McDonald's and other low-cost restaurants.
McDonald's says the company sells billions of portions, and yet you are not given sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
At present, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour in accordance with federal and New York legislation.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually increased, but not too strong, and on average, their simple staff in New York get 8.90 US dollars an hour.
Less than she deserves no one in this expensive city.
I can't understand how it's possible to get in New York with so little money.
There was a time when almost a quarter of all American young people were behind the counter after school at McDonald's, but the young people still lived with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw in it the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, at interviews with McDonald's employees, people are constantly meeting me who complain that they have to get along with this pay and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the Forum of the Wall Street Journal, whose author says it is irresponsible to have children if you don't know how to feed them.
The participants of the protests, which started on Thursday at 6.30 a.m. in the morning before McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that the cashier and cooks of fast food restaurants receive a minimum wage of 15 US dollars an hour, which is more than double the current minimum wage.
They continued to demand the formation of trade unions in the fast-food sector.
The US law forbids the management of the company to stand in the way of this goal and to reject or release trade union members.
On the other hand, the management does not make it easy for them.
However, the creation of trade unions in the fast food sector is also difficult for objective reasons.
The most important reason is the high level of staff turnover.
Unsatisfied
There were also loud protests that day before many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The highlight of the protests was a meeting at noon in front of McDonald's on Times Square, where some local democrats spoke, including city council member Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it sells billions of portions, and yet you are not allowed to get sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!"
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, Mayor candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should support the fast-food staff together so that they can get a fair reward and achieve the economic prosperity that every New York man deserves!."
According to New York Times, this was the biggest action of its kind in the history of the American fast-food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were on the ground, of which not all are employed in the fast-food sector in which tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet possible to see whether the spark of these protests will mobilize whole masses.
