"Mars and Venus," says the scientific assistant of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute of Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are relatively life-friendly, on the surface of Venus there is a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at a high level or in the orbit of Venus, that is, in space.
The question of reproduction in space was first addressed by the researchers with regard to the flora.
Experiments with plants were already carried out half a century before.
The fourth generation of the peas grown in orbit did not differ in the least from the earthly species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in the orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to space to explore the effect of weightlessness on the development of embryos.
A normal chick is developing.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a stop; it must be able to stand on its feet and start to move," explains the laboratory leader of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid ground, the chicks overtook themselves wild.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns were completely mute.
The chicks did not respond to light and loud.
Four days later, they just died.
"Twice we let chicks slip and then set it up because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev points out to the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, on the biosatellite "Bion" there will be only equal-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research must be continued," says Vladimir Sychev.
After the landing, the space rats were given offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not been solved so far.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, man could do that in principle.
The homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical considerations such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying to space for 50 years.
The greatest risk was in Tereschkowa.
The most valuable thing that humanity has is the female organism.
