Is that because the examiners are better there?
I certainly do not, but as I said, I do not like such comparisons very much.
To this end, it should be noted that those countries that are an example of us are also facing problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have any cooperation with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what was the importance of the revision of the procurement law for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet been effective in our tests.
As our controls are carried out retrospectively, there is a certain delay to be expected here.
So far, we have had more impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control instrument "detection of risks of uneconomic activity" and with this almost 14,000 public procurement is being examined and analysed - the changes will of course have an impact here, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of calls for tender have been modified, etc.
Do you see the adoption of this law more positive, or is the system being subject to further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be respected.
Under the previous rules, the persons subject to an examination are already accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to ensure that any failure to comply with the contract law is equivalent to an infringement of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even more stringent?
I do not think that is the way it is.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a form error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system only puts red tape under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let us say which path is not the target.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not involve entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now prohibited or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come to the chairman of the government, and the control office, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, is to obstruct its activities.
He can say, "We change the law and allow it," but he can't say that we act like nothing is.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal implementation of certain transactions - and this is also true for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded only due to malpractice.
The law will never be complete, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think is missing from us.
