Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think about that in less than a month of the world's downfall?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people so much like to start on.
With our band The Tap Tap we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the world's downfall.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the world's downfall.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a country-wide benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
For this we want to use the marketing potential of the Maya calendar, the end of which is forecast for December 21 at 11: 10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on December 20, three concerts will take place at the same time in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be in about the time that the Maya calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a 12-hour time zone in front of us.
Who did this idea come from?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
In doing so, we do not only want to collect enough positive energy to prevent the world from falling, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we give this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and key chains against the world's downfall, with which people can also support us through www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap has also recorded, together with other performers, the so-called hymn against the world's downfall with the title "World downfall falls out."
The hymn on YouTube is already very popular today. Will it also sound at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and that the world's downfall does not take place...
The hymn is to be sung by all the performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the hymns are transmitted live in a direct connection from Czech television.
The text of the hymn comes from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you get to work with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We are trying to get these people involved in our projects.
It has been shown that most are interested in working with us and have fun.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the world's downfall?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education centre Studeo, where we have been working for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly assisted by lecturers who help them in different leisure activities.
As the students themselves do not have the means to visit the readers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be created, in which we will then move in with this project.
At each concert there are several groups and performers.
What criteria did you choose it for?
We wanted to set up a program that addresses all generations including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý appear.
You can find out everything else on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year, we would also like to play in the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the USA, then I would like to do so with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips in a logistical and organisational way?
It's not as bad as it appears at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair drivers, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage room. We also have to carry many instrument bags and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without any problems, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us that I have sometimes been surprised in part.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
With your travel abroad, you have a comparison of what is in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How did you experience these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, where everything works better than we do, we were just in Russia to witness that everything is still in its early stages in the East.
Moscow is absolutely not disabled in relation to Prague. There it is still unusual when someone is in the wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even a matter of course that a wheelchair driver is to be left in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we're after...
However, it should be noted that an improvement in the situation will always depend on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common that people with serious disabilities can also move independently in public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
It is not very common, however, that a larger group of disabled people are actively involved in social activity there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to create a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a maintainer at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxofon, among other things, I have established a music AG together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, has used to say, something is out of control (laughs).
But the band was only known in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that the cooperation with well-known singers has helped us, and we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and you can't see it to the outside, your own performance does not exist in some sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good readers, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to make it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I have felt the potential that things can be addressed differently.
In show business, one often copies the other today.
This is logical in its way, as everything new is considered with caution and only accepted after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the audience usually has is, of course, pity; this is only natural...
But this pity is absolutely unnecessary because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live a full life and develop, if they have the means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not only a progress for them, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something right, you cannot compromise in many things and you must also demand some discipline.
This is, however, quite normal in my view.
Some of us come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have two weeks of trial, that they have to do preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, the enthusiasm of many will disappear quickly.
This is how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them have been there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
