Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was included as the twenty-first member of this Space Authority at a Council of Ministers of the Member States of the European Space Agency ESA. Poland is the second member from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland to space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos were interested in space, with which they did not always have an understanding.
I would like to remind you, for example, of the presentation by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics."
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, which was founded by Robert Esault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important supporter of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognised contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earth-related side of the moon was named after him.
In 1925 a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the design and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the draisine.
The information is from the contemporary press only.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with missile-powered missiles.
The research was carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the documents that have been delivered that research had been carried out up to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photo-electric hunting rocket from Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the technical press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocker.
Both projects were concerned with the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczazovy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Other articles on space were published in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is given in 1954 in the November edition of the magazine Problem, in which four major articles of space are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was possible that the research of space would have a future.
In its early years in 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Federation of Space, founded in 1951, and in fact, the PTA became a member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was appointed Vice-President of the International Federation of Space.
He was in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been a major participant in the development of the very successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first started on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh entirely 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 the Błędów desert started flight tests with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another level of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe altitude winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was stopped.
The first RM-type missiles were the Meteor-1-missile developed from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the start weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which were different in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor 1A rocket had a transport room with 0.4 litres of capacity, Meteor 1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor 1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
In 1965-1968, the Meteor 2 missile was developed in the Aviation Institute, the first of which started flight tests in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
The accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites under the Intercosm programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
