In November 1979, a mob of demonstrators of Islamic students occupied the American Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they called for the delivery of the fallen sheep Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who for decades had maintained the patronage of his regime.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have severely damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the call of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to release the hostages made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been carried out by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home created a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carters against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo of the director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story, which gave the US a small victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the message, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them to cover up their true identity - they were travelling with Canadian passports as members of a film staff who allegedly visited the country of Drehorte for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltration," Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time, and the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but also a so-called "Caper Movie," i.e. the story of a successful piece of Husaar, such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the levels of mood in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironic and slightly overshadowed.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the office halls, on the phone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable relaunch of his career.
From a smiled actor has become a respectable director, and also as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic comments.
Argo is his third film after the Crimean No Children's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without grace (2010).
At the same time it is Affleck's first film, which does not play in the director's home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that the previous films of this director removed from the standard Hollywood.
But Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the initial sequence of the first aeration of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved with his team in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a basar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not really offer many exciting scenes in the film sense.
But he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes helping the reality - which does not always look so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is turned off from a phone call in America, or the chase on the runway, have a little effect).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide spread, which is due to the need to have to show too much in action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their figures would have earned more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film thus loses some of its tensile strength. It is a film that can be followed with a certain interest and which can be considered to be the design and the retro-style that is reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th years.
However, he is very difficult to gain enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that has been living in a certain way today, and as a proof of how overstretched the ideas are of the omnipotent and all-knowing intelligence services, it is sufficient.
